# Step 1 — Introducing an Event

Let's begin with a simple question.

What exactly should be allowed to travel through our EventBus?

Without any restrictions, all of these become legal.

```java
eventBus.publish("Hello");
```

```java
eventBus.publish(42);
```

```java
eventBus.publish(new File("orders.csv"));
```

Clearly, these are not events.

They are simply arbitrary Java objects.

We need a way to express intent.

That's where a **marker interface** comes in.

Unlike a normal interface, a marker interface doesn't define any methods.

Its purpose is simply to identify a category of objects.

Our Event interface is therefore surprisingly small.

```java
package com.pristinum.eventbus;

public interface Event {
}
```

Every domain event in our application will implement this interface.

---

# Step 2 — Defining Events

An event represents something that has already happened.

Notice the tense.

Events describe facts.

They don't represent commands.

Let's define two events.

```java
package com.pristinum.eventbus.events;

import com.pristinum.eventbus.Event;
import com.pristinum.domain.Order;

public record OrderPlacedEvent(Order order)
        implements Event {
}
```

Another event.

```java
package com.pristinum.eventbus.events;

import com.pristinum.eventbus.Event;
import com.pristinum.domain.Payment;

public record PaymentCompletedEvent(Payment payment)
        implements Event {
}
```

Records work particularly well here because events are immutable by nature.

Once an order has been placed, that fact shouldn't change.

---

# Step 3 — The Listener Contract

In Part 2 we generalized all listeners into a single generic interface.

That remains unchanged.

```java
package com.pristinum.eventbus;

@FunctionalInterface
public interface EventListener<T extends Event> {

    void onEvent(T event);

}
```

This interface is intentionally tiny.

Every listener simply receives an event and reacts to it.

---

# Step 4 — What Should an EventBus Remember?

Before writing methods, let's think about state.

Suppose we register three listeners.

```
OrderPlacedEvent
    ├── EmailListener
    ├── AnalyticsListener
    └── WarehouseListener
```

Later we register payment listeners.

```
PaymentCompletedEvent
    ├── InvoiceListener
    └── FraudDetectionListener
```

Conceptually, this is nothing more than a mapping.

```
Event Type
        ↓
List of Listeners
```

That naturally becomes

```java
Map<
    Class<? extends Event>,
    List<EventListener<? extends Event>>
>
```

Now we're ready to implement the EventBus.

---

# Step 5 — Creating the EventBus

Let's start with the skeleton.

```java
package com.pristinum.eventbus;

import java.util.List;
import java.util.Map;
import java.util.concurrent.ConcurrentHashMap;
import java.util.concurrent.CopyOnWriteArrayList;

public class EventBus {

    private final Map<
            Class<? extends Event>,
            List<EventListener<? extends Event>>
            > listeners = new ConcurrentHashMap<>();

}
```

This is the only state inside our EventBus.

Everything else is behaviour.

---

# Step 6 — Registering Listeners

Suppose we write

```java
eventBus.register(
        OrderPlacedEvent.class,
        new EmailListener());
```

If this is the first listener for `OrderPlacedEvent`, we need to create a list.

Otherwise, we simply append to the existing list.

Java's `computeIfAbsent()` expresses this beautifully.

```java
package com.pristinum.eventbus;

import java.util.List;
import java.util.Map;
import java.util.concurrent.ConcurrentHashMap;
import java.util.concurrent.CopyOnWriteArrayList;

public class EventBus {

    private final Map<
            Class<? extends Event>,
            List<EventListener<? extends Event>>
            > listeners = new ConcurrentHashMap<>();

    public <T extends Event> void register(
            Class<T> eventType,
            EventListener<T> listener
    ) {

        listeners
                .computeIfAbsent(
                        eventType,
                        key -> new CopyOnWriteArrayList<>())
                .add(listener);

    }

}
```

The method is generic because the EventBus should work for every event type, not just orders.

---

# Step 7 — Unregistering Listeners

Removing a listener is slightly more interesting.

First, we locate the list.

If no listeners exist, we're done.

Otherwise, remove the listener.

Finally, if the list becomes empty, remove the entire map entry.

```java
public <T extends Event> void unregister(
        Class<T> eventType,
        EventListener<T> listener
) {

    List<EventListener<? extends Event>> eventListeners =
            listeners.get(eventType);

    if (eventListeners == null) {
        return;
    }

    eventListeners.remove(listener);

    if (eventListeners.isEmpty()) {
        listeners.remove(eventType);
    }

}
```

Notice that unregistering one listener does **not** remove the event type.

Only when the final listener disappears do we remove the key.

---

# Step 8 — Publishing Events

Publishing is where most developers become uncomfortable.

Let's implement it first.

We'll explain the tricky part afterwards.

```java
@SuppressWarnings("unchecked")
public <T extends Event> void publish(T event) {

    List<EventListener<? extends Event>> eventListeners =
            listeners.get(event.getClass());

    if (eventListeners == null) {
        return;
    }

    for (EventListener<? extends Event> listener : eventListeners) {

        EventListener<T> typedListener =
                (EventListener<T>) listener;

        typedListener.onEvent(event);

    }

}
```

This completes our EventBus.

But there's one obvious question.

Why is there an unchecked cast?

---

# Understanding the Unchecked Cast

Our map stores listeners as

```java
EventListener<? extends Event>
```

The compiler knows each object is *some* kind of EventListener.

What it doesn't know is **which** event that listener accepts.

Fortunately, we do.

Consider registration.

```java
eventBus.register(
        OrderPlacedEvent.class,
        new EmailListener());
```

The EmailListener is stored under the key

```
OrderPlacedEvent.class
```

Later, when we publish

```java
eventBus.publish(
        new OrderPlacedEvent(order));
```

we retrieve listeners using the exact same key.

```
listeners.get(OrderPlacedEvent.class)
```

Every listener in that list was registered specifically for an `OrderPlacedEvent`.

The compiler cannot infer this relationship.

The EventBus can.

That's why the cast is safe.

It's also why almost every generic EventBus implementation you'll encounter contains this exact unchecked cast.

```
The compiler lacks the context.

The EventBus doesn't.
```

---

# The Complete EventBus

```java
package com.pristinum.eventbus;

import java.util.List;
import java.util.Map;
import java.util.concurrent.ConcurrentHashMap;
import java.util.concurrent.CopyOnWriteArrayList;

public class EventBus {

    private final Map<
            Class<? extends Event>,
            List<EventListener<? extends Event>>
            > listeners = new ConcurrentHashMap<>();

    public <T extends Event> void register(
            Class<T> eventType,
            EventListener<T> listener
    ) {

        listeners
                .computeIfAbsent(
                        eventType,
                        key -> new CopyOnWriteArrayList<>())
                .add(listener);

    }

    public <T extends Event> void unregister(
            Class<T> eventType,
            EventListener<T> listener
    ) {

        List<EventListener<? extends Event>> eventListeners =
                listeners.get(eventType);

        if (eventListeners == null) {
            return;
        }

        eventListeners.remove(listener);

        if (eventListeners.isEmpty()) {
            listeners.remove(eventType);
        }

    }

    @SuppressWarnings("unchecked")
    public <T extends Event> void publish(T event) {

        List<EventListener<? extends Event>> eventListeners =
                listeners.get(event.getClass());

        if (eventListeners == null) {
            return;
        }

        for (EventListener<? extends Event> listener : eventListeners) {

            EventListener<T> typedListener =
                    (EventListener<T>) listener;

            typedListener.onEvent(event);

        }

    }

}
```

